{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"Migrations are applied in ascending numeric order determined by the filename prefix.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure risk is in module handoff (filesystem discovery -> filename parsing/sorting -> execution/recording), not just a pure sort function. A unit test of sorting alone can miss wiring bugs. System was considered but rejected because the behavior text does not require subprocess/OS-level effects; a single-process test with real modules and local DB/filesystem gives the needed reality signal.","test_description":"Create a temp migrations directory with out-of-order files (e.g., 001, 010, 002) whose SQL writes their version into a probe table. Run the real runner once against a test Postgres DB, then read back probe rows and _migrations rows to assert execution happened in numeric ascending order.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.14,"Integration":0.76,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"A migration that has already been applied is not re-executed on a subsequent run.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"This is idempotency across runner state and _migrations metadata, which is a multi-module interaction. Unit-only tests can miss real state handoff issues between execution and metadata persistence. Higher levels were rejected: no explicit subprocess/OS requirement and no AI dependency in behavior text.","test_description":"Run the runner twice against the same test DB with migrations that create observable side effects. After run 2, assert no duplicate side effects and no duplicate _migrations entries; verify previously applied versions were skipped.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.81,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run are attempted.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"Rollback/stop behavior depends on interaction between runner control flow and database transaction handling, which unit tests alone can fake incorrectly. System was considered but rejected because the behavior text does not require subprocess/OS-level validation; this can be proven with integrated modules against a test DB in one process. No LLM/multi-agent dependency.","test_description":"Prepare three migrations: first succeeds, second intentionally fails after making a change within its transaction scope, third would write a sentinel if reached. Run runner and assert: second migration effects are absent (rolled back), third migration not applied, and _migrations contains only completed versions before failure.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.68,"System":0.24,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances.","required_reality_check_level":"System","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires concurrent execution from separate processes. This is real subprocess/OS scheduling plus external DB locking/visibility, which unit/integration-in-process tests can miss. It also requires round-trip proof that side effects are exactly-once across both runners.","test_description":"Start two real runner processes simultaneously against the same test Postgres instance and shared migrations directory. Wait for both to exit, then read back domain tables and _migrations to assert each migration’s effect appears exactly once and each version is recorded once.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.14,"System":0.83,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the _migrations table is created before any migration file is applied.","required_reality_check_level":"Integration","justification":"This is bootstrap ordering across initialization and migration-application modules with DB state, so unit-only tests can miss sequencing bugs. System was considered but rejected because behavior text does not require subprocess/OS/network characteristics beyond normal local DB/filesystem integration; no AI dependency.","test_description":"Use a fresh empty test DB and migrations where the first migration can only succeed if _migrations already exists (or verify ordering via readback after run). Execute runner once and assert _migrations exists and migration files were applied in the same run with correct metadata persisted.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.08,"Integration":0.79,"System":0.11,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]}
